{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538828"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:33:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:33:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16392"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616435"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16392"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16392"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.22,0.06,0.55,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9083"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90668"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40408"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with community-acquired pneumonia. During routine blood tests, her total calcium is noted to be 2.85 mmol/L (2.10-2.60) with an ionised calcium of 1.48 mmol/L (1.15-1.30). She has a medical history of hypertension, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications are indapamide, amlodipine, pantoprazole, and glucosamine. She is currently receiving intravenous ceftriaxone and azithromycin for her pneumonia. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is alert and oriented with no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to her hypercalcaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pantoprazole","Amlodipine","Ceftriaxone","Indapamide","Glucosamine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with mild hypercalcaemia discovered incidentally during admission. The ionised calcium of 1.48 mmol/L (1.15-1.30) confirms true hypercalcaemia. Ionised calcium represents the physiologically active form of calcium and is the most accurate measure of calcium status, as it is unaffected by albumin levels or acid-base disturbances. While corrected calcium formulas were historically used to adjust for albumin levels, direct measurement of ionised calcium is now preferred when available, as it provides a more reliable assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndapamide\u003C/strong\u003E is a thiazide-like diuretic that can cause hypercalcaemia by reducing urinary calcium excretion. This is a well-documented side effect of thiazide and thiazide-like diuretics. The mechanism involves increased calcium reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule, leading to reduced calcium excretion and subsequent elevation in serum calcium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, does not typically affect calcium homeostasis and would not contribute to hypercalcaemia. Despite its name, calcium channel blockers work by blocking calcium entry into vascular smooth muscle and cardiac cells rather than affecting serum calcium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucosamine\u003C/strong\u003E is a supplement commonly used for osteoarthritis that has no direct effect on calcium metabolism and would not contribute to hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPantoprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is a proton pump inhibitor used for gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. While proton pump inhibitors can affect calcium absorption in the long term (potentially leading to hypocalcaemia), they do not cause hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E does not typically affect calcium metabolism or cause hypercalcaemia. While ceftriaxone can rarely cause biliary pseudolithiasis due to calcium-ceftriaxone precipitation, this does not affect serum calcium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management would involve considering cessation of the thiazide-like diuretic and switching to an alternative antihypertensive medication. Further investigation of other causes of hypercalcaemia (such as primary hyperparathyroidism or malignancy) may still be warranted, particularly if the hypercalcaemia persists after medication adjustment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ionised calcium is the physiologically active form and is more reliable than total or corrected calcium for assessing true calcium status.","Thiazide and thiazide-like diuretics can cause hypercalcaemia by increasing renal calcium reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule.","Medication review is essential when evaluating hypercalcaemia, as several commonly prescribed drugs can contribute to elevated calcium levels."],"references":["Turner JJO. Hypercalcaemia - presentation and management\u2002. Clin Med (Lond). 2017 Jun;17(3):270-273. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.17-3-270. PMID: 28572230; PMCID: PMC6297576.","Duarte CG, Winnacker JL, Becker KL, Pace A. Thiazide-Induced Hypercalcemia. New England Journal of Medicine, 284, 15, 828-830. doi 0.1056/NEJM197104152841506. Available from: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM197104152841506."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90668"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16392"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90668"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T21:01:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T17:50:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"